## George Gordon, 4th Earl of Huntly

George Gordon, the 4th Earl of Huntly, was a figure of considerable consequence in the tumultuous landscape of 16th-century [Scotland](/Scotland). Born in 1514, he navigated a world where loyalty was a fluid commodity and power was often seized through brute force or cunning diplomacy. He died on 28 October 1562, leaving behind a legacy as complex and formidable as the man himself. His title, [Earl of Huntly](/Earl_of_Huntly), was inherited from his grandfather, [Alexander Gordon, 3rd Earl of Huntly](/Alexander_Gordon,_3rd_Earl_of_Huntly), and would eventually pass to his second son, [George Gordon, 5th Earl of Huntly](/George_Gordon,_5th_Earl_of_Huntly). His marriage to [Elizabeth Keith](/Elizabeth_Keith,_Countess_of_Huntly) produced a brood of twelve children, a testament to both his lineage and his dynastic ambitions. Among them were notable figures such as [George](/George_Gordon,_5th_Earl_of_Huntly), [Jean](/Jean_Gordon,_Countess_of_Bothwell), [James](/James_Gordon_(Jesuit)), [Adam](/Adam_Gordon_of_Auchindoun), and [Patrick](/Patrick_Gordon_of_Auchindoun), each destined to carve their own paths through history, for better or worse.

### Life

The trajectory of George Gordon's life was set from a young age. He inherited his earldom and the vast Gordon estates in 1524, a mere ten years old. This early accession thrust him into the unforgiving arena of Scottish power politics, where childhood was a luxury few could afford. His formative years were shaped by the constant ebb and flow of royal favour and the ever-present threat of internal strife.

His military prowess first came to the fore in 1542, when, as commander of the King's Army, he inflicted a decisive defeat upon the English at the [Battle of Haddon Rig](/Battle_of_Haddon_Rig). This victory, though significant, was but a prelude to the larger conflicts that would define his career. He later found himself a member of the [council of Regency](/Council_of_Regency), a position of immense influence, serving under the regency of [James Hamilton, 2nd Earl of Arran](/James_Hamilton,_2nd_Earl_of_Arran) and the formidable [Cardinal Beaton](/David_Beaton). Following Beaton's assassination in 1546, Gordon ascended to the position of [Chancellor](/Lord_Chancellor_of_Scotland), a role that placed him at the very apex of Scottish governance.

Yet, fortune is a fickle mistress. In 1547, Gordon experienced the harsh reality of defeat at the [Battle of Pinkie Cleugh](/Battle_of_Pinkie_Cleugh). This catastrophic loss resulted in his capture by the English and his subsequent confinement in the infamous [Tower of London](/Tower_of_London). It was not until the autumn of 1548 that his freedom was secured, bought with a substantial ransom delivered by [Robert Carnegie, Lord Kinnaird](/Robert_Carnegie,_Lord_Kinnaird). This period of captivity undoubtedly left its mark, a stark reminder of the precariousness of his position.

In 1550, a different kind of duty called. He accompanied Queen [Mary of Guise](/Mary_of_Guise) on her journey to France, a diplomatic mission that underscored his importance in the eyes of the Scottish crown. However, the winds of religious and political change were stirring. By 1560, Gordon found himself aligning with the [Lords of the Congregation](/Lords_of_the_Congregation), the Protestant faction that sought to reshape Scotland's religious landscape. His adherence, however, was described as "a late, reluctant, and unreliable recruit," a testament to his complex allegiances and perhaps his inherent conservatism. Despite his formal joining of the Protestant cause, he remained a deeply religious man, striving for "a form of co-existence between Catholic and reformed worship," a remarkably pragmatic stance in an era of fervent religious division.

Gordon was prepared to accept [Mary, Queen of Scots](/Mary,_Queen_of_Scots), and even accompanied her court upon her return to Scotland. Yet, his relationship with the young queen was to prove strained. In September 1561, a fall from his horse during a visit to [Dunbar Castle](/Dunbar_Castle) marked a physical vulnerability that foreshadowed his political downfall.

The true rupture came with Mary's decision to transfer the [Earldom of Moray](/Earl_of_Moray), an honour she had bestowed upon Huntly in 1549, to her ambitious half-brother, [Lord James Stewart](/James_Stewart,_1st_Earl_of_Moray). This perceived slight was a profound insult, and Huntly, deeply wounded, retreated to his ancestral estates in the North-East of Scotland. This withdrawal signaled a clear defiance, a refusal to bend to the queen's will.

Mary, determined to assert her authority, embarked on a royal tour of the north-east in August 1562. Her path was met with a direct challenge when Huntly, through his orders, denied her entry into [Inverness Castle](/Inverness_Castle). This act of open rebellion could not be ignored. The Queen's forces swiftly captured the castle, and she proceeded to [Aberdeen](/Aberdeen), where she issued a summons for Gordon. His refusal to appear before her was an act of treason, and he was subsequently [outlawed](/Outlaw).

Undeterred, Huntly raised his banners and marched on Aberdeen, a desperate gambit to reclaim his position. However, his forces were met and decisively defeated by [James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray](/James_Stewart,_1st_Earl_of_Moray) at the [Battle of Corrichie](/Battle_of_Corrichie) in October 1562. Huntly himself did not survive the aftermath. He died of [apoplexy](/Apoplexy) shortly after his capture, his reign ending not in triumph, but in the ignominy of defeat. His son, Sir John, would also meet a grim fate, executed in Aberdeen for his father's rebellion. Parliament, in May 1563, completed the ruin by posthumously forfeiting Huntly's titles and estates.

The indignity of his downfall extended even beyond the grave. After his death, his body and confiscated goods from [Strathbogie Castle](/Huntly_Castle) were transported from Aberdeen to [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh). His corpse was presented at his trial, a macabre spectacle meant to underscore his guilt. The seized possessions were delivered to [Holyrood Palace](/Holyrood_Palace). Years later, when Mary herself was imprisoned at [Lochleven Castle](/Lochleven_Castle), a fragment of her former glory was found with her: the earl's [cloth-of-estate](/Baldachin), a grim reminder of the shifting tides of power.

### Family

George Gordon's marriage to [Elizabeth Keith](/Elizabeth_Keith,_Countess_of_Huntley) on 27 March 1530 was a union that solidified his position and secured his lineage. Together, they produced a remarkable family of nine sons and three daughters. The sheer number of offspring speaks to the importance of dynastic continuity in an era of such instability. Among their children, several would rise to prominence:

*   **Thomas Gordon**: His life and achievements, though less documented than some of his siblings, were nonetheless part of the Gordon legacy.
*   **[George Gordon, 5th Earl of Huntly](/George_Gordon,_5th_Earl_of_Huntly)**: He would inherit his father's title and strive to restore the family's fortunes, though not without his own share of political maneuvering.
*   **Lady Margaret Gordon**: Her marriage to John, Master of Forbes, son of [William Forbes, 7th Lord Forbes](/William_Forbes,_7th_Lord_Forbes), tied the Gordon name into another influential Scottish house.
*   **Lady [Jean Gordon, Countess of Bothwell](/Jean_Gordon,_Countess_of_Bothwell)** (1546 – 14 May 1629): Her life was a saga in itself, marked by her tempestuous marriage to the infamous James Hepburn, 4th Earl of Bothwell, and later to Alexander Lindsay, 1st Earl of Crawford. She was a woman of resilience, enduring significant personal and political upheaval.
*   **Lady Elizabeth Gordon** (died 1557): Her early death was a loss to the family, and her marriage to [John Stewart, 4th Earl of Atholl](/John_Stewart,_4th_Earl_of_Atholl) further cemented alliances.
*   **Alexander Gordon, Lord Gordon** (d. 1553): His early death was a blow to the succession, and his marriage to [Barbara Hamilton](/Barbara_Hamilton_(courtier)) connected the family to another prominent lineage.
*   **Sir John Gordon of [Findlater](/Findlater_Castle)**: His involvement in a bitter feud with [James Ogilvie of Cardell](/James_Ogilvie_of_Cardell) led to his execution in 1562, a direct consequence of his father's rebellion.
*   **[James Gordon](/James_Gordon_(Jesuit))** (born 1541): He would later pursue a path of religious service, becoming a prominent [Jesuit](/Jesuit).
*   **[Adam Gordon of Auchindoun](/Adam_Gordon_of_Auchindoun)** (born 1545): His life, while lacking detailed records for his early years, was part of the broader Gordon narrative.
*   **[Patrick Gordon of Auchindoun](/Patrick_Gordon_of_Auchindoun)**: Another son who carried the Gordon name into subsequent generations.

There is also a curious footnote regarding a potential additional daughter. A letter from Edward Stanhope to the [Earl of Essex](/Robert_Devereux,_2nd_Earl_of_Essex), dated 6 December 1598, identifies Richard Rutherford of Hunthill as a "cousin german to Earl Huntly." If Stanhope's genealogical assertion holds true, it implies that George Gordon, the 4th Earl, may have fathered yet another daughter:

*   **(daughter) Gordon**, who married John Rutherford of Hunthill.

### Ancestry

The roots of George Gordon, 4th Earl of Huntly, ran deep into the soil of Scottish nobility. His lineage was a tapestry woven with threads of power, prestige, and royal blood.

*   His paternal grandfather was **[George Gordon, 2nd Earl of Huntly](/George_Gordon,_2nd_Earl_of_Huntly)**, a figure who helped establish the family's prominence.
*   His father was **[John Gordon, Lord Gordon](/John_Gordon,_Lord_Gordon)**, who predeceased him, thus passing the earldom directly from the grandfather. His paternal grandmother was **Annabella of Scotland**, a link to the Scottish royal house.
*   His maternal grandfather was **[John Stewart, 1st Earl of Atholl](/John_Stewart,_1st_Earl_of_Atholl)**, a significant figure in his own right. His maternal grandmother was **[Margaret Douglas, Fair Maid of Galloway](/Margaret_Douglas,_Fair_Maid_of_Galloway)**, a woman whose lineage was steeped in power and tragedy.
*   This maternal line connected him directly to the Scottish crown through **[James IV of Scotland](/James_IV_of_Scotland)**, his maternal grandfather, and **[Margaret Drummond](/Margaret_Drummond_(mistress))**, his maternal grandmother. Margaret Drummond, a lady of considerable beauty and influence, met a tragic end, a detail that adds a somber hue to the otherwise grand tapestry of his ancestry.
*   Further back, his maternal line traced through **[James III of Scotland](/James_III_of_Scotland)** and **[Margaret of Denmark](/Margaret_of_Denmark,_Queen_of_Scotland)**, solidifying his royal connections. His maternal great-grandmother was **[Euphemia de Ross](/Euphemia_de_Ross)**, and his maternal great-great-grandfather was **[Robert II of Scotland](/Robert_II_of_Scotland)**, further entrenching his claim to royal descent. On his mother's side, he was also descended from **[John Drummond, 1st Lord Drummond](/John_Drummond,_1st_Lord_Drummond)** and **Elizabeth Lindsay**.

This intricate web of noble and royal connections provided George Gordon with a powerful foundation, a heritage that both shaped his ambitions and, ultimately, contributed to the dramatic circumstances of his downfall. He was a product of his time, a man whose life was a testament to the enduring power and perilous nature of Scottish aristocracy.